Rules for writing hamza in the Arabic script

Rules for writing hamza in the Arabic script

الحمد لله والصلاة والسلام على نبينا محمد. أما بعد:

1 Introduction

The rules of hamzaḧ orthography in the Arabic script are quite complex. The matter is further complicated by the limitations of metal and digital typography technology. We attempt to give a comprehensive set of rules for writing hamzaḧ and some recommendations for typographers and typesetters.

2 Disclaimer

This article is based on findings from the author’s research and may have errors. Any errors reported to the author’s email will be greatly appreciated.

3 Scope

We treat only the orthography of Standard Arabic. The orthography of the Qurʾān (الرسم العثماني) is not discussed.

4 hamzaḧ orthography

4.1 Different ways hamzaḧ is written

hamzaḧ is written in four different ways:

  1. Seated on an ʾalif: أ or إ
  2. Seated on an wāw: ؤ
  3. Seated on an yāʾ: ئ
  4. Unseated: ء

Here are some of notes about writing hamzaḧ in the above four methods:

  • When unseated hamzaḧ is followed by an ʾalif: ءا, the combination of hamzaḧ and ʾalif is usually written as آ as a convention. Examples: آمَنَ ʾāmana, ظَمْآن ḏ̣amʾān, شَنَآن šanaʾān. However, when the ʾalif is a suffix or part of a suffix, or the hamzaḧ is doubled, or there is an ʾalif before the hamzaḧ then we will write ءا, not آ. Examples: شَيْءَانِ šayʾāni, سَءَّال saʾʾāl, قِرَاءَات qirāʾāt.

  • When unseated hamzaḧ comes between two letters that are joined, then it is written above the line that joins them, for example: خَطِيءَة xaṭīʾaḧ. In this word, the yāʾ ي joins to the tāʾ marbūṭaḧ ة.

  • When hamzaḧ is seated on ʾalif, if it has an kasraḧ, it is written below the ʾalif: إِ. Otherwise, it is written above the ʾalif: أَ, أُ, أْ.

  • When hamzaḧ is seated on yāʾ ئ the dots of the yāʾ are no longer written. Here’s how it will appear in different positions:

    Isolated End Middle Beginnning
    ئ ـئ ـئـ ئـ

    Note that hamzaḧ is seated on yāʾ in the middle position ـئـ is different from unseated hamzaḧ between two joining letters ـءـ.

So how do we know when to write hamzaḧ unseated and when seated? And how do we choose between its three different seats? There are a set of rules that we need to follow in order to correctly write hamzaḧ.

4.2 Ordered set of rules

  1. If hamzaḧ occurs in the beginning of a word:
    1. If the hamzaḧ carries a long-ā vowel, it is written unseated followed by an ʾalif and written as آ, for example آمَنَ ʾāmana.
    2. If the hamzaḧ carries any other vowel, it is written seated on an ʾalif, and is marked with the appropriated vowel mark, for example أَسْلَمَ ʾaslama, أُرِيدُ ʾurīdu, إِسْلَام ʾislām, إِيمَان ʾīmān, أُوخِذَ ʾūxiḏa.
  2. If hamzaḧ occurs in the middle of a word:
    1. If there is a long vowel or diphthong before the hamzaḧ:
      1. If the hamzaḧ is after a long-ī vowel or ay diphthong, then the hamzaḧ will be written unseated. Examples:
        هَيْءَة hayʾaḧ, خَطِيءَة xaṭīʾaḧ
        بَرِيءُونَ barīʾūna, بَرِيءَانِ barīʾāni, بَرِيءِينَ barīʾīna, بَرِيءَيْنِ barīʾayni
        شَيْءُهُ šayʾuhu, شَيْءَهُ šayʾahu, شَيْءِهِ šayʾihi, شَيْءَانِ šayʾāni, شَيْءَيْنِ šayʾayni
        مَجِيءُهُ maǧīʾuhu, مَجِيءَهُ maǧīʾahu, مَجِيءِهِ maǧīʾihi
      2. If the hamzaḧ is after a long-ū vowel or aw diphthong, then:
        1. If the hamzaḧ has an kasraḧ it is written seated on yāʾ. Examples: سُوئِهِ sūʾihi, ضَوْئِهِ ḍawʾihi
        2. Otherwise, the hamzaḧ is written unseated. Examples: سُوءَهُ sūʾahu, سُوءَانِ sūʾāni, تَوْءَم tawʾam, ضَوْءَهُ ḍawʾahu, ضَوْءَانِ ḍawʾāni, سُوءُهُ sūʾuhu, يَسُوءُونَ yasūʾūna
      3. If the hamzaḧ is after a long ā-vowel, then:
        1. If the hamzaḧ has an kasraḧ it is written seated on yāʾ. Example: سَائِل sāʾil.
        2. If the hamzaḧ has an ḍammaḧ it is written seated on wāw. Example: تَسَاؤُل tasāʾul.
        3. Otherwise, when the hamzaḧ has an fatḥaḧ, it is written unseated. Example: تَسَاءَلَ tasāʾala, قِرَاءَات qirāʾāt.
    2. If the letter before the hamzaḧ has a sukūn and is not wāw or yāʾ (in which case rule 2.a would apply), then:
      1. If the hamzaḧ was originally at the end of the word, but a suffix has been attached to the word such that the hamzaḧ is now in the middle of the word, then the hamzaḧ will be written unseated. Examples: عِبْءَانِ ɛibʾāni, عِبْءَيْنِ ɛibʾayni, بُطْءَهُ buṭʾahu, بُطْءُهُ buṭʾuhu, بُطْءِهِ buṭʾihi. (انِ, يْنِ, هُ, and هِ are suffixes).
      2. Otherwise, if the hamzaḧ is originally at the middle of the word, then:
        1. If the hamzaḧ has a ḍammaḧ it is written seated on wāw. Example: مَسْؤُول masʾūl.
        2. If the hamzaḧ has a kasraḧ it is written seated on yāʾ. Example: تَرْئِيس tarʾīs.
        3. If the hamzaḧ has an fatḥaḧ then:
          1. If it is followed by a long-ā vowel represented by an ʾalif, the hamzaḧ is unseated followed by the ʾalif and the combination is written as آ. Example: مِرْآة mirʾāḧ, ظَمْآن ḏ̣amʾān.
          2. Otherwise, if there is no ʾalif after the hamzaḧ, the hamzaḧ is written seated on ʾalif. Examples: مَسْأَلَة masʾalaḧ, , الْمَرْأَة almarʾaḧ.
    3. If the hamzaḧ has a sukūn, then look at the vowel mark on the letter preceding it:
      1. If the letter preceding hamzaḧ has a kasraḧ, the hamzaḧ is written seated on yāʾ. Example: بِئْسَ biʾsa.
      2. If the letter preceding hamzaḧ has a ḍammaḧ, the hamzaḧ is written seated on wāw. Example: سُؤْلَكَ suʾlaka.
      3. If the letter preceding hamzaḧ has a fatḥaḧ, the hamzaḧ is written seated on ʾalif. Example: كَأْس kaʾs.
    4. Otherwise, only if the above conditions are not satisfied, then compare the vowel marks of the hamzaḧ and the letter before it:
      1. If either vowel mark is an kasraḧ then the hamzaḧ will be written on a yāʾ. Examples: سُئِلَ suʾila, يَئِسَ yaʾisa, مُتَّكِئِينَ muttakiʾīna, رَئِيس raʾīs.
      2. If neither vowel mark is an kasraḧ, and at least one of the vowel marks is a ḍammaḧ, then the hamzaḧ will be written on a wāw. Examples: سُؤَال suʾāl, رُؤُوس ruʾūs, لُؤَيّ luʾayy.
      3. Otherwise, if both of the vowel marks are fatḥaḧs, then:
        1. If the hamzaḧ is followed by a long-ā vowel represented by an ʾalif, the hamzaḧ is written unseated. Examples: شَنَآن šanaʾān.
        2. Otherwise the hamzaḧ will be written on an ʾalif. Examples: سَأَلَ saʾala, رَأَىٰ raʾā.
      These set of rules apply even if the hamzaḧ or the previous letter is doubled. Examples رَأَّسَ raʾʾasa, يُرَئِّسُ yuraʾʾisu, رُئِّسَ ruʾʾisa, تَفَؤُّل tafaʾʾul, يُبَرِّئُونَ yubarriʾūna, يُبَرَّؤُونَ yubarraʾūna, سَءَّال saʾʾāl, لَءَّال laʾʾāl.
  3. If hamzaḧ is at the end of a word, disregard the vowel mark on it and consider only the letter before the hamzaḧ.
    1. If there is a long vowel (ā, ī, ū) or a diphthong (aw, ay) before it then the hamzaḧ will be written unseated. Examples: دُعَاءُ duɛāʾu, سُوءُ sūʾu, جِيءَ ǧīʾa, ضَوْءَ ḍawʾa, شَيْءَ šayʾa.
    2. Otherwise, if the previous letter has a sukūn, the hamzaḧ will again be unseated. Examples: بُطْءُ buṭʾu, عِبْءُ ɛibʾu, شَطْءُ šaṭʾu
    3. Otherwise, if the previous letter is a doubled wāw with an ḍammaḧ, the hamzaḧ will again be unseated. Example تَبَوُّءُ tabawwuʾu.
    4. Otherwise, if the previous letter has an:
      1. kasraḧ, the hamzaḧ is written seated on yāʾ. Example يُهَدِّئُ yuhaddiʾu, سَيِّئُ sayyiʾu.
      2. ḍammaḧ, the hamzaḧ is written seated on wāw. Example بَطُؤَ baṭuʾa.
      3. fatḥaḧ, the hamzaḧ is written seated on ʾalif. Example يَهْدَأُ yahdaʾu, مُبْتَدَإِ mubtadaʾi.

4.3 Prefixes and suffixes

  • If hamzaḧ is in the beginning of a word, adding a prefix to the word will not alter the writing of the hamzaḧ. Examples: لِ + أُسْتَاذِ = لِأُسْتَاذِ.

  • If hamzaḧ is at the end of a word, adding a suffix to the word can, in general, alter the writing of the hamzaḧ, except in cases that have already been mentioned above. Examples:
    مُبْتَدَأَ + انِ = مُبْتَدَءَانِ
    دُعَاءُ + هُ = دُعَاؤُهُ
    ضَوْءِ + هِ = ضَوْئِهِ
    بُطْءُ + هُ = بُطْءُهُ

  • As we mentioned earlier, when unseated hamzaḧ is followed by an ʾalif which is not a suffix: ءا, the combination of hamzaḧ and ʾalif is conventionally written as آ. However, if the unseated hamzaḧ is doubled or preceded by another ʾalif then it won’t be written as آ. Example: سَءَّال saʾʾāl, قِرَاءَات qirāʾāt.

5 tanwīn on final hamzaḧ

tanwīn on a final hamzaḧ does not affect the writing of the hamzaḧ except in the case of tanwīn al-fatḥ. When writing tanwīn al-fatḥ on a hamzaḧ at the end of a word:

  1. If there is an ʾalif before a unseated hamzaḧ اء, then we don’t add a silent ʾalif when writing tanwīn al-fatḥ. For example دَاء becomes دَاءً dāʾan, not دَاءًا.

  2. Otherwise, we add the silent ʾalif after the hamzaḧ so that the hamzaḧ is now in the middle of the word with a suffix ʾalif after it. We now pretend that the hamzaḧ has an fatḥaḧ and that the ʾalif after it is a long-ā vowel. Then we go through the rules for writing hamzaḧ in the middle of a word (given above) to determine how hamzaḧ will be written. We then write the an-mark on the hamzaḧ. For example مُبْتَدَأ becomes مُبْتَدَءًا mubtadaʾan, مُبْتَدِئ becomes مُبْتَدِئًا mubtadiʾan, بُطْء becomes بُطْءًا buṭʾan, شَيْء becomes شَيْءًا šayʾan.

6 Variants

There are some historical and geographical variants to the above rules. The main one is a variant of rule 2.b.ii above. In this variant, when the letter before hamzaḧ has a sukūn, the hamzaḧ is generally written unseated. So they write:

  • مَسْءُول instead of مَسْؤُول
  • أَسْءِلَة instead of أَسْئِلَة
  • مَسْءَلَة instead of مَسْأَلَة

However, this rule appears to not consistently be followed. For example, al-marʾaḧ is generally always written الْمَرْأَة never الْمَرْءَة.

A second variant is to write hamzaḧ unseated when:

  1. it has a ḍammaḧ and is followed by a long-ū vowel. Example: رُءُوس instead of رُؤُوس.
  2. it has a kasraḧ and is followed by a long-ī vowel. Example: رَءِيس instead of رَئِيس.

7 Typographical limitations

Due to what appears to have been a limitation of typographical technology in the days of typewriters, metal typrography, and early digital typography, unseated hamzaḧ between two joining letters ـءـ was usually written as seated on yāʾ instead: ـئـ. Because of this limitation we are now accustommed to seeing:

  • شَيْئًا instead of شَيْءًا
  • خَطِيئَة instead of خَطِيءَة
  • هَيْئَة instead of هَيْءَة
  • عِبْئَيْنِ instead of عِبْءَيْنِ

and similar variants.

These variants have pervaded to such a degree that many modern treatises on the rules of hamzaḧ orthography present the above as the correct way of writing, and modify their rules with exceptions to allow this writing.

Fortunately, advancements in digital typography technology now allow us to revert back to the original rules. However, unfortunately, only very few computer fonts today actually implement this feature.

Two fonts, of which we are aware, that do allow the preferred orthography are:

  1. Dr Khaled Hosny’s “Amiri”: https://www.amirifont.org/
  2. DecoType “Naskh”: https://www.decotype.com/oneliner/

With these “hamzaḧ-safe fonts” you can always use U+0621 “Arabic Letter Hamza” to type unseated hamzaḧ no matter whether it is between joining or non-joining letters. With most other fonts U+0621 “Arabic Letter Hamza” will prevent the surrounding two letters from joining.

We recommend that Arabic typographers implement this much needed feature as has been implemented in the two fonts mentioned above.

This issue has been discussed in detail by Thomas Milo in Unicode L2/14-109: https://unicode.org/L2/L2014/14109-inline-chars.pdf.

We may also mention that there is a way of faking the correct orthography with most fonts. This is to write a combination of U+0640 “Arabic Tatweel” and U+0654 “Arabic hamza above” thus ـٔ to achieve the appearance of unseated hamzaḧ between two joining letters. However, this will not work when hamzaḧ is between lām and ʾalif in the mandatory lam-ʾalif ligature لا (correct: لءا, incorrect: لـٔا). This may also affect the searching of characters in a digital document so we are hesitant to recommend this hack.
